> > An employee of radio shack told me they were getting out of the car
> > audio business, so this might be coming up to your last chance to get
> > one of these imitation gems.
>
>
>They do have very cheap prices on whatever car stereo is left.  Yes, I 
>know,
>Radio Shack isn't exactly top of the line car audio.  But I picked up a few
>pieces to put in my Crew Cab and my Mini Cooper (neither of which has
>interior acoustics that would do justice to audiophile gear, especially 
>when
>driving down the road), and was actually very surprised at how decent they
>sounded.  I got up a pair of 5-1/4" 3-way car speakers reduced from around
>$80 to $15, their better 3-way 6x9s (they have 2 models) reduced from $100
>to $39, a pair of 6x9 carpeted speaker boxes for about $10, a 3-way
>electronic crossover for $15, and monster bridgeable 4/3/2 channel amp
>marked down from $250 to $99 (and supposedly stable into 2 ohms, no less!).
>For around $150 combined my expectations weren't high, but they were
>certainly more than surpassed.  I'd put the performance on the par with
>lower to mid range models from Pioneer, Kenwood, etc. that would have cost
>much more.  I have an indash MP3 player so I didn't get a head unit, but
>they did have blow-outs on a few indash units (one of them shaft-mount, the
>others detachable face).  Worth checking out if you want to outfit your bus
>with music on the cheap. Get the clerk to check inventory in other local
>stores, as they can order in items from other locations if another branch
>has what you want.  If the clerk is helpful he can scroll through various
>models in their point-of-sale computer and often stumble upon older models
>that aren't in the latest catalog, but still in stock somewhere and very
>heavily reduced.
>
